article.description: Tracy McGrady scored 26 points and Horace Grant added 21, leading the Orlando Magic to a 102-91 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Magic go over .500 for first time in a month
article.linkText: Magic hold off Sixers, eclipse .500 for first time in a month
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Tracy McGrady wasn't about to come out of this game.
McGrady

McGrady scored 26 points and Horace Grant added 21, leading the Orlando Magic to a 102-91 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Wednesday night. "Tracy wouldn't allow me to take him out," Magic coach Doc Rivers said. "I'm a smart coach. I listen. He wanted to play all 48 minutes. He didn't want to lose. He's the key, like a (Michael) Jordan and (Allen) Iverson. Our guys feed off him. Orlando has won four straight to go over the .500 mark for the first time since Dec. 8. Philadelphia, which had won three of four after losing 13 of 18, fell to 15-20. The defending Eastern Conference champions lost just 26 games last season. Iverson scored 27 points and Dikembe Mutombo had 13 points and 20 rebounds for the Sixers. Iverson, coming off his first career triple-double on Monday night, shot just 4-of-13 in the second half and finished 12-of-28. "We're just not like the team we were last year," Iverson said. "We were much better defensively and had more offensive chemistry. We were just a much better team. A lot of stuff goes on on the court that didn't last year and nobody does anything about it. The effort is not the same and our effort isn't the same." The Sixers used a 9-2 run to cut it to 81-80 midway through the fourth on a layup by Eric Snow. But Pat Garrity drilled a 3-pointer and, after a layup by Derrick Coleman, Darrell Armstrong made a layup and Grant hit a jumper to give the Magic an 88-82 lead. After a driving layup by Iverson, McGrady got fouled by Snow from way behind the 3-point line as the shot clock wound down. McGrady hit all three free throws to make it 91-84 with 3:16 left. Grant then hit a jumper for a 93-84 lead with 2:34 left. The Sixers didn't get closer than six the rest of the way. "We executed well on offense and played great defense," McGrady said. "I wasn't going to come out. I wasn't tired and there's no way we were going to lose this game." Mike Miller had 18 points, including four 3-pointers, and nine rebounds for the Magic. He had 27 points, nine rebounds and five assists in a 98-87 victory over Boston on Monday night. The Magic hit 10 of 19 from 3-point range. Grant, starting at center in place of the injured Patrick Ewing, shot 9-of-15. "I haven't seen Horace Grant step up like that since he played for the Bulls," Sixers forward Matt Harpring said. Orlando took its biggest lead, 44-33, following a 12-2 run in the second. The Magic started the spurt with eight straight points, including five by Monty Williams. The Sixers scored just one basket over a stretch of 6:43, but cut it to 47-43 with 30 seconds left in the first half after a 10-3 run. "We did a great job of spacing the floor," Rivers said. "I'm most impressed with the way we shared the ball. This is a big win for us. I don't care what Philadelphia's record is. They are one of the best teams in the East."

Game notes
Former Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy worked the game as an analyst for TNT. ... Ewing was placed on the injured list with tendinitis in his right Achilles' and calf. ... The Sixers wore headbands for the fifth straight game, a sign of unity after reports that coach Larry Brown was going to quit. ... Sixers reserve Corie Blount didn't play because of an ankle injury. ... Harpring had 12 points and 11 rebounds. ... Philadelphia outrebounded Orlando 47-34.
